          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- About -->
        <article id="about" class="panel">
          <header>
            <h2>About Spam and Eggs</h2>
          </header>

          <h3>Source</h3>
          <p>
            You can download the source, or let me know about problems
            on
            <a href="https://github.com/iantruslove/spam-and-eggs">
              GitHub</a>.
          </p>

          <h3>Models</h3>
          <p>
            The personal information is generated from a couple of
            lists of common names and email domains, plus some basic
            frequency distribution models. I use the generators in
            <a href="https://github.com/clojure/test.check">test.check</a>
            to select items from lists, because it makes it really easy.
          </p>

          <p>
            Using demographic data to get common first and last name
            frequencies, it's possible to generate eerily familiar
            names and email addresses. If you know anybody generated
            by this site list, I promise it's just a
            coincidence...
          </p>

          <p>
            The email text is generated with
            a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_chain">Markov
            chain</a>. There is only one model currently in use, and
            it was trained on the first couple of paragraphs from
            Douglas Adams' "Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy". (You'd
            never guess what I'm reading right now.)
          </p>

          <h3>Tech</h3>
          <p>
            Spam and Eggs is written in Clojure, and hosted
            by <a href="http://www.heroku.com"> Heroku
            </a>. Both of these are quite great.
          </p>

